comment: Offset -1.4. Printing 3x dog bones. 1500 µL T2. Okay-defined dog bones with minor overcuring, but ageing of ink noticeable (less "crisp" edges at relatively high exposure time, stalk not uniformly thick but a bit distorted). 2/3 with partially delaminated stalks (between layers 1 and 2; still attached to prints). Prints stick strongly to printhead -> damaging to lower side of prints notable when collecting with spatula. Single intact dog bone collected and 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can: sample P1. Keyence and storage at 4 °C.
next steps: Prepare 1 mL more T2 to buff ink and increase exposure time.

comment: Rotary table rotated manually. Printing 3x dog bones. Ca. 400 µL of T2 from run #1 (collected with pipet) mixed in tube with unused rest of T2 plus 1 mL freshly prepped T2. 1500 µL of this mix pipetted to a different, clean spot on the FEP film (->avoid reuse of "aged" FEP film). Prints stick strongly to printhead as before and are damaged slightly during detachment. Definition generally better than in #1, but slight overcuring and distorted stalk. 1/3 with partially delaminated stalk (between layers 1 and 2; still attached to print) > discarded.  1/3 with bubble (ca. 1 mm) in head close to stalk, the other with no defects -> samples P2.2 and P2.1. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.
next steps: Direct re-printing, but decrease exposure in layer 1.

comment: Printing 3x dog bones. Remaining ink of run #2 at same spot -> too little: dog bones at side are missing parts at heads. Additionally, one of these with complete delamination of layer 2 (stuck on FEP) -> discarded. Middle print superb with best definition so far/virtually no overcuring -> sample P3.1. Other print sample P3.2. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.

Rotary table rotated manually to print in new spot on FEP film. Printing 1x dog bone. 700 µL T3. Detachment with new broad spatula -> superb. Dog bone with no delamination and defects but usual one-sided overcuring. Sample P4. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.
next steps: Clean ink vat. Decrease exposure time.

comment: Printing 1x dog bone. 700 µL T3. Detachment with new broad spatula -> superb.  Dog bone well-defined, bit less overcuring than in run #4. Sample P5. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.

Printing 1x dog bone. Rest T3 from run #5 +300 µL fresh T3. Detachment with new broad spatula -> superb. Dog bone well-defined, much less overcuring than in run #5, almost none. Air bubble left hole in one head, but irrelevant to testing. Sample P6. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.

Rotary table rotated manually to print in new spot on FEP film. Printing 1x dog bone. 700 µL T3. Detachment with new broad spatula -> superb. Dog bone perfectly defined, virtually no overcuring. Sample P7. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.

Rotary table rotated manually to print in new spot on FEP film. Printing 3x dog bones. 1500 µL T1. Detachment with new broad spatula -> superb. Okay-defined dog bones with minor overcuring but stalks not uniformly thick/a bit distorted, similar to prints of run #1 (theory: stronger adhesion distorts/partly shifts between layers). All 3 prints intact. Samples P8.1, P8.2 and P8.3. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.

Printing 2x dog bones. Rest T1 from run #8 +rest fresh T1. Detachment with new broad spatula -> superb. 1/2 prints with partial delamination/defect in stalk -> discarded. Other print intact, with less distortion/shifts in stalk than in run #8, but still existent. Sample 9. 10 min post-curing in DPBS in 385 nm paint can, Keyence and storage at 4 °C.
